list.item:
Copies of news reports to Thomas Errington, retired merchant, August 26,
                     1822-January 20, 1823, and other notes and copies of letters, April 17,
                     1923-January 18, 1833. Pp. [189-199];

scopecontent.p:
Massachusetts. To Joseph Bradley Varnum, Washington, D.C. Glorious success of
                  navy; amen to votes of Congress to augment it;
                  dissatisfaction with unsuccessful manner in which war has been prosecuted on land;
                  need 40,000 regulars and as many volunteers as will join to enter the enemy’s
                  territory.

Order to the forage master to deliver to the Beaver corn for his horses that
                  brought whisky into the camp which was seized and taken by the officer of the day;
                  & which corn must be accounted for in settlement for the whisky.

Groton, Massachusetts. To Joseph Bradley, Varnum, Washington, D.C. Local affairs;
                  resignation of Hampton, arrest of Wilkinson, removal of Granger; so disgraceful a campaign as our last was never
                     known; politics.

Company book of Capt. Isaac Curtiss: regimental, brigade and general orders;
                  record of disciplinary action; account of United States arms and equipage dealt
                  out to the company; list of deserters.

list.item:
Appended to the receipt is an itemized bill, Mar. 29-June 13, 1815;
                     documents certifying the account ;is justly due, De. 13, 1816; and a note by
                     Andrew Jackson that the claim should be paid, Feb. 28, 1817.
